This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing (NLP) tasks such as lemmatization and morphological tagging. Additionally, the paper mentions achieving state-of-the-art results on 20 languages from the Universal Dependencies corpora, which is a common benchmark dataset used in NLP research. 

The paper also uses neural models, indicating that it could potentially belong to the sub-categories cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

Furthermore, the paper mentions error analysis and the effectiveness of joint morphological tagging and lemmatization in low-resource languages and those with a larger degree of morphological complexity, suggesting that it could potentially belong to the sub-categories cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.CY (Computers and Society).
